`src/pages/Library.tsx:29-33` ‚Äî every `BookCard` calls `useAllProgress()` indirectly via the shared store and recomputes `bookStats(book)` on **every render**, for **every book**, whenever **any single book's** progress changes anywhere in the app.

The root cause is in `src/lib/progress.ts:45-50`: `update()` spreads the *entire* `ProgressState` map into a new object on every mutation:
```ts
store.set((s) => ({
  ...s,
  [bookId]: { ...sanitize(s[bookId]), ...patch, updatedAt: Date.now() },
}))
```
Since `useAllProgress()` (`progress.ts:36-38`) returns that whole object via `useSyncExternalStore`, marking chapter 3 of *Book A* as read gives a new object reference to `useAllProgress()` subscribers ‚Äî which re-renders **every** `BookCard` in the library, including books untouched by the change. Each of those re-renders redoes `bookStats(book)` (word counts + reduces over all chapters) for no reason.

**Fix:** scope each card to its own book's progress and memoize the card:
```tsx
// Library.tsx
const BookCard = React.memo(function BookCard({ book, step }: { book: Book; step?: number }) {
  const progress = useBookProgress(book.id)   // subscribes only to this book's slice
  const stats = useMemo(() => bookStats(book), [book])
  const pct = completionPct(book.map.chapters.length, progress)
  ...
})
```
`useBookProgress` already exists (`progress.ts:40-43`) and does the same `sanitize(all[bookId])` ‚Äî it's just not used here. Swapping it in still re-renders on unrelated updates today because `useSyncExternalStore` returns the same `all` object reference check, but combined with `React.memo` and passing only `book`/`progress` as props, unrelated cards stop re-rendering once you select from the store with a proper equality check, or simpler: derive `progress` in the parent once via `useAllProgress()` and pass `all[book.id]` down as a prop with `React.memo`'s default shallow-prop comparison (won't help since `all` is a new ref) ‚Äî the cleanest fix is a per-key selector store. Minimal version: memoize `bookStats` (below) so the redundant call is at least cheap, and wrap `BookCard` in `React.memo`.

**`content.ts:110-145` `loadChapter`** re-parses the same markdown (regex splitting into key-ideas/in-practice/body, plus `mdToHtml`) every time it's called ‚Äî including navigating back to a chapter you already visited in the same session. The underlying dynamic import is cached by the browser module system, but the parsing work is not. Add a simple in-memory cache since chapter content is static for the app's lifetime:
```ts
const chapterCache = new Map<string, Chapter>()

export async function loadChapter(bookId: string, n: number): Promise<Chapter | null> {
  const key = `${bookId}/${n}`
  const cached = chapterCache.get(key)
  if (cached) return cached
  const loader = chapterIndex.get(bookId)?.get(n)
  if (!loader) return null
  const raw = await loader()
  // ...existing parsing...
  const chapter = { number: n, title, words, minutes, keyIdeas, bodyHtml: mdToHtml(bodyMd), inPractice }
  chapterCache.set(key, chapter)
  return chapter
}
```

**`content.ts:154-164` `bookStats`** is a pure function of `Book`, and `Book` objects are static module-level data (loaded once via `import.meta.glob`). It's currently recomputed from scratch (word-counting every chapter summary) on every call ‚Äî once per `BookCard` render, plus once per book in `Library.tsx:109-113`'s totals `useMemo`. Cache by book id:
```ts
const statsCache = new Map<string, BookStats>()
export function bookStats(b: Book): BookStats {
  const cached = statsCache.get(b.id)
  if (cached) return cached
  // ...existing computation...
  const stats = { mapMinutes, deepMinutes, totalMinutes, distilledPages, originalMinutes, savedPct }
  statsCache.set(b.id, stats)
  return stats
}
```

**`markdown.tsx:5-7` `mdToHtml`** ‚Äî `MapChapterCard` (`BookMap.tsx:42`) calls `<Markdown text={chapter.summary}>` for every chapter, and that re-parses the summary through `marked.parse` on every `BookMap` re-render (e.g. every time you toggle "Map was enough" on any chapter, since that flips `progress` state and re-renders the whole map list). Chapter summaries are static strings ‚Äî memoize by content:
```tsx
const htmlCache = new Map<string, string>()
export function mdToHtml(src: string): string {
  let html = htmlCache.get(src)
  if (html === undefined) {
    html = marked.parse(src, { async: false }) as string
    htmlCache.set(src, html)
  }
  return html
}
```
(Uncapped cache is fine here ‚Äî the input set is the fixed corpus of book/chapter markdown, not user-generated text.)

**`content.ts:173-192` `searchBooks`** ‚Äî for every keystroke, iterates all books and for each one calls `categoryOf(b)` (`content.ts:69-71`, a linear `.find()` over categories) and rebuilds/lowercases three template strings, even though `strong`/`mid`/`weak` don't change between searches for the same book. Since `books` and `categories` are static, precompute the searchable, lowercased strings once at module load instead of on every call:
```ts
const searchIndex = books.map((b) => ({
  book: b,
  strong: `${b.title} ${b.author}`.toLowerCase(),
  mid: `${b.tagline} ${categoryOf(b)?.name ?? ''}`.toLowerCase(),
  weak: b.map.chapters.map((c) => c.title).join(' ').toLowerCase(),
}))

export function searchBooks(query: string): Book[] {
  const q = query.trim().toLowerCase()
  if (!q) return books
  const terms = q.split(/\s+/)
  return searchIndex
    .map(({ book, strong, mid, weak }) => {
      let score = 0
      for (const t of terms) {
        if (strong.includes(t)) score += 5
        if (mid.includes(t)) score += 2
        if (weak.includes(t)) score += 1
      }
      return { book, score }
    })
    .filter((x) => x.score > 0)
    .sort((x, y) => y.score - x.score)
    .map((x) => x.book)
}
```

**`AudioPlayer.tsx:16`** ‚Äî `touchDevice` correctly is computed once at module load (good pattern), but `voiceScore` (`tts.ts:77-91`) does several `.includes()` calls per voice, re-run for the full voice list on every `AudioPlayer` render as noted in ¬ß2 ‚Äî folding that into the `voicesVersion`-keyed memo fixes both the re-render and the redundant computation in one change.

---

**Priority if you want to tackle a subset:** #1 (progress store causing library-wide re-renders) and the `voicesForUi()` memo in #2 are the two with real user-visible impact ‚Äî the first degrades with library size, the second runs continuously during every audio session. The caching items in #3 are cheap wins with no behavior change since all the underlying data is static.

